comment: Quetta's morning air quality is "moderately unhealthy" - time for some spicy chai and deep breathing.
With a PM2.5 of 67 and AQI of 159, the air in Islamabad at 6am feels more like a morning smoothie.
Abbottabad's morning air quality is 'meh' - not terrible, but could use a breath of fresh air.
Looks like Charsadda's morning air is a bit hazy - better grab those masks before heading out!
At 5 AM in DI Khan, the air is worse than a hot dog vendor's cart - PM2.5 of 97.6 and AQI of 180.
Haripur's air quality is a bit of a mixed bag - not too shabby, but not exactly a breath of fresh air either.
Mohmand Agency's morning air is refreshingly breathable, no need for a hazmat suit just yet.
Peshawar's air quality is 'unhealthy' - time to don a hazmat suit for your morning chai!
At 5AM in Swabi, the air is thick as pea soup, with PM2.5 levels that would make a Londoner cough.
Faisalabad's morning air is like a smog-filled sauna - bring a gas mask and a swimsuit!
Lahore's morning smog is so thick, you could slice it and serve it on toast.
At 6AM, Mangla's PM2.5 of 49 μg/m³ and AQI of 134 suggest a sleepy start to a hot, hazy day.
Multan's air quality at 6 AM is 'Unhealthy' with PM2.5 levels high enough to make you cough up a storm.
At 6 AM, the air in Rahim Yar Khan has a PM2.5 that could double as a smoke machine.
At this early hour, the air in Rawalpindi seems a bit hazy - time to bust out the face masks!
Sialkot's morning air is a brisk 183 on the AQI, perfect for an early morning jog through the smog!
At 6AM in Karachi, the air is a bit smokey - the PM2.5 is high enough to make you cough over your morning chai.
At 6 AM in Sukkur, the air is a whopping 384 on the AQI - that's a smog sauna!
